mission_data.title: Starlink Group 9-8
mission_data.description: SpaceX launch of a batch of Starlink v2-mini satellites for their second generation high-speed low earth orbit internet satellite constellation. The mission will likely include a mix of Direct-to-Cell and normal v2-Mini Starlink satellites.

title: SpaceX Crew-9
description: First crewed launch from SLC-40. After NASA decided to return Starliner's Crewed Flight Test (CFT) vehicle uncrewed, it was decided that Crew-9 would launch with only 2 crew members of the originally intended 4, and land with the added 2 Starliner CFT crew.
location: SLC-40, Cape Canaveral SFS, Florida, USA
mission_data.title: SpaceX Crew-9
mission_data.description: SpaceX Crew-9 is the ninth operational crewed rotation mission of a Crew Dragon spacecraft to the International Space Station. The original intended crew comprised Commander Zena Cardman, Pilot Nick Hague, Mission Specialist Stephanie Wilson, and Roscosmos cosmonaut Mission Specialist Aleksandr Gorbunov.

title: Unknown Payload
description: Launch vehicle and payload identities uncertain.
location: Site 9401 (SLS-2), Jiuquan Satellite Launch Center, China

title: IGS-Radar 8
location: LA-Y1, Tanegashima Space Center, Japan
mission_data.title: IGS-Radar 8
mission_data.description: The IGS-Radar 8 is a Japanese radar reconnaissance satellite. The satellite is operated by the Cabinet Satellite Information Center. The satellite serves both Japan's national defense and civil natural disaster monitoring.

title: OneWeb #20
location: SLC-4E, Vandenberg SFB, California, USA
mission_data.title: OneWeb #20
mission_data.description: The 20th flight dedicated to the OneWeb high-speed Internet constellation. The initial constellation consists of 648 satellites. Later, the constellation could be expanded to more than 900 satellites depending on demand. OneWeb is expected to begin customer demonstrations in 2022, then provide a global, 24-hour service in 2022/2023.

title: Unknown Payload
description: Payload and launch vehicles identities extremely uncertain.
location: Site 95A, Jiuquan Satellite Launch Center, China

title: Glonass-K1 n°18L
location: Plesetsk Cosmodrome, Russia
mission_data.title: Glonass-K1 n°18L
mission_data.description: GLONASS-K is the latest satellite design intended as a part of the Russian GLONASS radio-based satellite navigation system. Developed by ISS Reshetnev (Reshetnev Information Satellite Systems) and first launched on 26 February 2011, it is a substantial improvement of the previous GLONASS-M second-generation satellites, having a longer lifespan and better accuracy.

title: Certification Flight 2
location: SLC-41, Cape Canaveral SFS, Florida, USA
mission_data.title: Certification Flight 2
mission_data.description: Replacement Vulcan test launch with inert payload, experiments, and demonstrations for certification with the USSF after delays caused by payload testing of the Sierra Space Dreamchaser CRS SNC-1 mission, the original planned payload.

title: Hera
location: SLC-40, Cape Canaveral SFS, Florida, USA
mission_data.title: Hera
mission_data.description: Hera is a space mission of the European Space Agency whose objective is to validate the kinetic impact method to deflect a possible asteroid circulating on a collision course with the Earth. The satellite will study the results obtained by the DART impactor developed by NASA which successfully crashed into the Dimorphos asteroid in September 2022.

title: Europa Clipper
location: LC-39A, Kennedy Space Center, Florida, USA
mission_data.title: Europa Clipper
mission_data.description: Europa Clipper will conduct a detailed survey of Europa and use a sophisticated suite of science instruments to investigate whether the icy moon has conditions suitable for life. Key mission objectives are to produce high-resolution images of Europa's surface, determine its composition, look for signs of recent or ongoing geological activity, measure the thickness of the moon’s icy shell, search for subsurface lakes, and determine the depth and salinity of Europa's ocean.

title: Kirameki 3
location: LA-Y2, Tanegashima Space Center, Japan
mission_data.title: Kirameki 3
mission_data.description: DSN-3, also known as Kirameki 3, is a geostationary communications satellite to be operated by DSN Corporation, a subsidiary of SKY Perfect JSAT Group. Its payload is a pure X band and will be used for military communications by the Japanese military.

title: USSF-106
description: First Vulcan rocket to support a NSSL mission.
location: SLC-41, Cape Canaveral SFS, Florida, USA
mission_data.title: NTS-3
mission_data.description: NTS-3 (Navigation Technology Satellite 3) is a demonstration navigation satellite. NTS-3 will experiment with a new digital signal generator that can be reprogrammed on-orbit, enabling it to broadcast new signals, improve performance by avoiding and defeating interference, and adding signatures for detecting spoofing attacks.

title: CRS SpX-31
location: SLC-40, Cape Canaveral SFS, Florida, USA
mission_data.title: CRS SpX-31
mission_data.description: SpaceX CRS-31 is a Commercial Resupply Service mission to the International Space Station. The mission is contracted by NASA and will be flown by SpaceX using a Cargo Dragon.

title: Koreasat 6A
location: SLC-40, Cape Canaveral SFS, Florida, USA
mission_data.title: Koreasat 6A
mission_data.description: The Koreasat 6A spacecraft, built by Thales Alenia Space, will have 20 transponders for fixed satellite services and six for TV broadcasting to replace the Koreasat 6 launched in 2010.

title: Lockheed Martin Demo 1
location: SLC-2W, Vandenberg SFB, California, USA
mission_data.title: Lockheed Martin Demo 1
mission_data.description: First of up to 25 launches of Low Earth Orbit technology demonstration satellites to be built and operated by Lockheed Martin. Launch operation will also again demonstrate responsive space pre-launch operation capabilities.

title: SXM-9
location: SLC-40 or LC-39A, Florida, USA
mission_data.title: SXM-9
mission_data.description: SXM-9 is the 10th high-powered, digital, audio radio satellite built by Maxar (SSL) for SiriusXM. The SXM-9 satellite will be based on Maxar’s proven 1300-class platform and built at the company’s manufacturing facility in Palo Alto, California. It is expected that SXM-9 will launch in 2024.  SXM-9 has a large, mesh, unfurlable reflector almost 10 meters in diameter that allows SiriusXM programming to reach its radios, including those in moving vehicles.

title: Ionosfera-M n°1, 2 & Others
location: Site 1S, Vostochny Cosmodrome, Russia
mission_data.title: Ionosfera-M n°1 & 2
mission_data.description: Ionosfera is a constellation of four ionospheric and magnetospheric research satellites developed by for Roscosmos for the project Ionozond.

title: Progress MS-29
location: Site 31/6, Baikonur Cosmodrome, Kazakhstan
mission_data.title: Progress MS-29
mission_data.description: Progress (in Russian: "Прогресс") MS-29 is a Russian cargo vehicle which will resupply the International Space Station. This will be the 182nd flight of a Progress.

title: PROBA 3
location: First Launch Pad, Satish Dhawan Space Centre, India
mission_data.title: PROBA 3
mission_data.description: PROBA-3 will be composed of two independent, three-axis stabilized spacecraft flying 150 meters from one another with the ability to accurately control the attitude and separation of the two craft. It will be maintained for 6 hours, creating ″artificial solar eclipse″ for the satellite below. The spacecraft pair will fly a highly elliptical orbit divided between periods of accurate formation flying around apogee, when payload operations will be possible, and periods of free flight. The length of the formation control period will be a trade-off involving the increasing amount of fuel needed to maintain the orbits in formation when away from apogee.

title: GSAT-20 (GSAT-N2)
location: SLC-40 or LC-39A, Florida, USA
mission_data.title: GSAT-20 (GSAT-N2)
mission_data.description: GSAT-20 is a communication satellite jointly being developed by Indian Space Research Organisation Satellite Centre and Liquid Propulsion Systems Centre. GSAT-20 will be a continuation of GSAT series of communication satellites. The satellite is intended to add data transmission capacity to the communication infrastructure required by Smart Cities Mission of India.

title: Demo Flight
location: Wenchang Space Launch Site, China
mission_data.title: Demo Flight
mission_data.description: Demo Flight, cargo unknown

title: Sentinel-1C
description: Originally intended to launch on the Russian Soyuz launch vehicle, due to geopolitical factors this is no longer an option. ESA instead opted to launch aboard Vega-C.
location: ELV, Guiana Space Centre, French Guiana, France
mission_data.title: Sentinel-1C
mission_data.description: Sentinel-1C will provide all-weather, day, and night radar imaging for land and ocean services.

title: Kondor-FKA n°2
location: Site 1S, Vostochny Cosmodrome, Russia
mission_data.title: Kondor-FKA n°2
mission_data.description: The Kondor-FKA is a small civilian radar Earth observation satellite designed by NPO Mashinostroyeniya as a civilian counterpart to the Kondor-E satellite.

title: Blue Ghost Mission 1
location: SLC-40 or LC-39A, Florida, USA
mission_data.title: Blue Ghost Mission 1
mission_data.description: Blue Ghost is a commercial lunar lander developed by Firefly Aerospace for NASA’s CLPS program. Blue Ghost is designed to bring up to 155kg of payload to the lunar surface. It will land at Mare Crisium in the Crisium Basin and is designed to last 14 days before freezing in the lunar night.

title: WorldView Legion 5 & 6
location: SLC-40 or LC-39A, Florida, USA
mission_data.title: WorldView Legion 5 & 6
mission_data.description: Currently being built by SSL, WorldView-Legion is DigitalGlobe's next generation of earth observation satellites.

title: Transporter 12
location: SLC-4E, Vandenberg SFB, California, USA
mission_data.title: Transporter 12
mission_data.description: Transporter 12 is a dedicated rideshare mission by SpaceX. SpaceX’s SmallSat Rideshare Program provides small satellite operators with regularly scheduled, dedicated Falcon 9 rideshare missions to SSO for ESPA class payloads for as low as $300,000 per mission, which includes up to 50kg of payload mass.

title: Shenzhou 19
location: Site 901 (SLS-1), Jiuquan Satellite Launch Center, China
mission_data.title: Shenzhou 19
mission_data.description: Shenzhou 19 (Chinese: 神舟十九号), the flight will mark the 14th crewed Chinese spaceflight and the nineteenth flight of the Shenzhou program. The spacecraft will carry three People's Liberation Army Astronaut Corps (PLAAC) taikonauts on the eighth flight to the Tianhe core module, the first module of the Tiangong space station.

title: Kinéis 11-15
location: Māhia Peninsula, New Zealand
mission_data.title: Kinéis 11-15
mission_data.description: Third batch of five satellites for the French Kinéis IoT constellation designed to operate with 25 nanosatellites of 30 kg each. The constellation will enable Kinéis, a company backed by private and public investors including the French government’s space agency CNES (Centre National d'Études Spatiales) and CLS (Collecte Localisation Satellites) an international space-based solutions provider, to improve its global IoT connectivity.

title: 425 Project Flight 3
location: SLC-40 or LC-39A, Florida, USA
mission_data.title: 425 Project Flight 3
mission_data.description: Launch of the third satellite in a contract of 5 reconnaissance satellites for the South Korean Defense Acquisition Program Administration (DAPA), with 1 satellite featuring an electro-optical infrared (EO/IR) telescope. The other 4 synthetic aperture radar (SAR) satellites are to be launched at a later date.

title: Starship Flight 5
description: Fifth flight of Starship and Super Heavy. Full mission profile has not been announced but it's thought to be similar to Flight 4.
location: Orbital Launch Pad A, Starbase, Texas, USA
mission_data.title: Starship Flight 5

mission_data.title: Maiden Flight
mission_data.description: Maiden flight of the New Glenn launch vehicle. Will carry the prototype Blue Ring payload tug and payload hoisting platform, in addition to serving as New Glenn's first National Security Space Launch certification flight.

title: NZSA Venus Mission
description: First private Venus mission. First interplanetary mission launched on Electron, and from New Zealand.
location: Māhia Peninsula, New Zealand
mission_data.title: NZSA Venus Mission

mission_data.title: CSO-3
mission_data.description: The French CSO (Composante Spatiale Optique) high-resolution reconnaissance satellites are the optical space component of the MUSIS program that will replace the current Hélios 2 military observation satellites.

title: CRS SpX-32
location: SLC-40 or LC-39A, Florida, USA
mission_data.title: CRS SpX-32
mission_data.description: SpaceX CRS-32 is a Commercial Resupply Service mission to the International Space Station. The mission is contracted by NASA and will be flown by SpaceX using a Cargo Dragon.

title: HAKUTO-R M2 “Resilience”
location: SLC-40 or LC-39A, Florida, USA
mission_data.title: HAKUTO-R M2 “Resilience”
mission_data.description: HAKUTO-R is a multinational commercial lunar exploration program operated by ispace. It includes ispace's first two lunar missions, the second mission will perform a soft landing on the Moon and deployment of a rover developed by ispace in 2024. In addition to its studies on the moon's surface, the rover is expected to collect lunar regolith as part of a contract with NASA signed in 2020 in which companies will collect materials on the moon and then transfer ownership "in situ" to the agency.

title: SPAINSAT New Generation I
location: SLC-40 or LC-39A, Florida, USA
mission_data.title: SPAINSAT New Generation I
mission_data.description: SPAINSAT NG is Hisdesat's largest project since its foundation. Its technological complexity and strategic relevance will position the company as an international benchmark in satellite communications. The new Spainsat NG generation will multiply by 16 times the capacity in X and Ka military band with respect to the current devices and will add a new payload in UHF band. In addition, it will operate with active X-band antennas in receive and transmit. Pioneers in the European aerospace sector, each of them will be assigned 16 different areas of operation to perform their coverage services with electronic configuration.

title: Bandwagon-2
location: SLC-40 or LC-39A, Florida, USA
mission_data.title: Bandwagon-2
mission_data.description: Bandwagon-2 is a dedicated rideshare mission by SpaceX. SpaceX’s SmallSat Rideshare Program provides small satellite operators with regularly scheduled, dedicated Falcon 9 rideshare missions to mid-inclination orbits for ESPA class payloads for as low as $300,000 per mission, which includes up to 50kg of payload mass.

title: Kinéis 16-20
location: Māhia Peninsula, New Zealand
mission_data.title: Kinéis 16-20

The constellation will enable Kinéis, a company backed by private and public investors including the French government’s space agency CNES (Centre National d'Études Spatiales) and CLS (Collecte Localisation Satellites) an international space-based solutions provider, to improve its global IoT connectivity.

title: Tianzhou 8
location: LC-201, Wenchang Space Launch Site, China
mission_data.title: Tianzhou 8
mission_data.description: The Tianzhou (Chinese: 天舟; lit. 'Heavenly Ship') is a Chinese automated cargo spacecraft developed from China's first prototype space station Tiangong-1 to resupply its future modular space station. It was first launched (Tianzhou 1) on the Long March 7 rocket on April 20, 2017, and demonstrated autonomous propellant transfer (space refueling).

title: Demo Flight
location: Commercial LC-1, Wenchang Space Launch Site, China

title: Fram2
location: SLC-40 or LC-39A, Florida, USA
mission_data.title: Fram2
mission_data.description: Named in honor of the ship that helped explorers first reach Earth’s Arctic and Antarctic regions, the mission commander will be Chun Wang, an entrepreneur and explorer who co-founded f2pool and stakefish. The vehicle commander will be Jannicke Mikkelsen, a film director, and cinematographer. The vehicle pilot will be Eric Philips, a professional polar adventurer and guide who has completed ski expeditions to the North and South Poles. The final crew member will be mission specialist Rabea Rogge, a robotics researcher from Berlin, currently pursuing her PhD in Norway.

title: Flight 2
description: Payload to be confirmed.
location: Space One Launch Pad, Space Port Kii, Japan

title: Resurs-P No.5
location: Site 31/6, Baikonur Cosmodrome, Kazakhstan
mission_data.title: Resurs-P No.5
mission_data.description: Resurs-P is a series of Russian commercial Earth observation satellites capable of acquiring high-resolution imagery (resolution up to 1.0 m). The spacecraft is operated by Roscosmos as a replacement for the Resurs-DK No.1 satellite.

title: Obzor-R n°1 & Others
location: Plesetsk Cosmodrome, Russia
mission_data.title: Obzor-R n°1
mission_data.description: The Russian Obzor-R satellite is a planned X-band radar earth observation satellite designed by TsSKB-Progress.

title: Project Kuiper
location: SLC-41, Cape Canaveral SFS, Florida, USA
mission_data.title: Project Kuiper
mission_data.description: Project Kuiper is a mega constellation of satellites in Low Earth Orbit that will offer broadband internet access, this constellation will be managed by Kuiper Systems LLC, a subsidiary of Amazon. This constellation is planned to be composed of 3,276 satellites. The satellites are projected to be placed in 98 orbital planes in three orbital layers, one at 590 km, 610 km and 630 km altitude.

title: Thuraya 4-NGS
location: SLC-40 or LC-39A, Florida, USA
mission_data.title: Thuraya 4-NGS
mission_data.description: Thuraya 4-NGS is a communication satellite being built by Airbus Defense and Space for the UAE based Yahsat.

title: Elytra Mission 1
location: SLC-2W, Vandenberg SFB, California, USA
mission_data.title: Elytra Mission 1
mission_data.description: Elytra Mission 1 will demonstrate the responsive on-orbit capabilities of the Elytra vehicle. In support of Xtenti’s follow-on study contract with the NRO, the mission will demonstrate a rapid payload reconfiguration utilizing Xtenti’s FANTM-RiDE payload dispenser prior to launching on Firefly’s Alpha vehicle. Upon launching on Alpha, Firefly’s Elytra vehicle will utilize the FANTM-RiDE dispenser to first deploy commercial rideshare payloads in Sun-Synchronous Orbit, and then perform an on-orbit maneuver and stand ready to deploy U.S. government payloads on-demand.

title: BlackSky Gen-3 Mission 1
location: Māhia Peninsula, New Zealand
mission_data.title: BlackSky Gen-3 Mission 1
mission_data.description: The first of five BlackSky Technology missions to deploy its new next-generation BlackSky Gen-3 satellites. The commercial constellation of Gen-3 satellites has the capability to produce imagery with 50-centimeter resolution and host multiple sensors, including shortwave infrared (SWIR). The improved resolution and enhanced spectral diversity of the Gen-3 satellites will expand BlackSky's ability to provide real-time information to its customers.

title: Glonass-K1 n°19L
location: Plesetsk Cosmodrome, Russia
mission_data.title: Glonass-K1 n°19L
mission_data.description: GLONASS-K is the latest satellite design intended as a part of the Russian GLONASS radio-based satellite navigation system. Developed by ISS Reshetnev (Reshetnev Information Satellite Systems) and first launched on 26 February 2011, it is a substantial improvement of the previous GLONASS-M second-generation satellites, having a longer lifespan and better accuracy.

title: CRS SNC-1
description: First flight of the Dream Chaser spaceplane.
location: SLC-41, Cape Canaveral SFS, Florida, USA
mission_data.title: CRS SNC-1
mission_data.description: The Dream Chaser Cargo System is an American reusable spaceplane being developed by Sierra Nevada Corporation (SNC) Space Systems. The Dream Chaser is designed to resupply the International Space Station with both pressurized and unpressurized cargo. The vehicle will launch vertically and autonomously land horizontally on conventional runways.

title: ViaSat-3 EMEA
location: SLC-41, Cape Canaveral SFS, Florida, USA
mission_data.title: ViaSat-3 EMEA (Europe, Middle East and Africa)
mission_data.description: The ViaSat-3 class of Ka-band satellites is expected to provide unprecedented capabilities in terms of service speed and flexibility for a satellite platform. The first two satellites will focus on the Americas and on Europe, Middle East and Africa (EMEA), respectively, with the third satellite planned for the APAC region, completing Viasat's global service coverage. Each ViaSat-3 class satellite is expected to deliver more than 1-Terabit per second of network capacity, and to leverage high levels of flexibility to dynamically direct capacity to where customers are located.

title: NAOS (LUXEOSys)
location: SLC-4E, Vandenberg SFB, California, USA
mission_data.title: NAOS (LUXEOSys)
mission_data.description: NAOS (National Advanced Optical System) is Luxembourg's military recon satellite.

title: GSAT-7R
location: Second Launch Pad, Satish Dhawan Space Centre, India
mission_data.title: GSAT-7R
mission_data.description: GSAT-7 is an advanced communication satellite built by ISRO to provide wide range of service spectrum from low bit rate voice to high bit rate data communication. GSAT-7 Communication payload is designed to provide communication capabilities to users over a wide oceanic region including the Indian land-mass. The payload configuration is compatible with I-2.5K bus of ISRO. The GSAT-7 payload design includes Multiband communication.

title: EOS-05
location: Second Launch Pad, Satish Dhawan Space Centre, India
mission_data.title: GISAT-2
mission_data.description: GEO Imaging Satellite or GISAT is a planned Indian geo-imaging satellite for providing images quickly during disasters.

title: HRSAT
location: Satish Dhawan Space Centre, India
mission_data.title: HRSAT
mission_data.description: HRSAT (High Resolution Satellite) is an Indian satellite constellation consisting of three satellites in a single orbital plane.

title: Cartosat-3B
location: Satish Dhawan Space Centre, India
mission_data.title: Cartosat-3B
mission_data.description: Cartosat-3 are a proposed series of remote sensing satellites from ISRO, which are intended to replace the IRS series. Cartosat-3 is an advanced version of Cartosat-2 series with improved spatial and spectral characteristics. It will have a panchromatic resolution of 0.25 metres and Mx of 1 metre which is a major improvement from the previous payloads in the Cartosat series. Potential uses include weather mapping, cartography, and strategic applications.

title: HTV-X 1

location: LA-Y2, Tanegashima Space Center, Japan
mission_data.title: HTV-X 1
mission_data.description: HTV-X 1 is the maiden flight of HTV-X. It is designed to be more affordable compared to the original H-II Transfer Vehicle (HTV). Like its predecessor, HTV-X vehicle will transport cargo to the International Space Station.

location: LA-Y2, Tanegashima Space Center, Japan
mission_data.title: Michibiki 5
mission_data.description: QZSS (Quasi Zenith Satellite System) is a Japanese satellite navigation system operating from inclined, elliptical geosynchronous orbits to achieve optimal high-elevation visibility in urban canyons and mountainous areas. The navigation system objective is to broadcast GPS-interoperable and augmentation signals as well as original Japanese (QZSS) signals from a three-spacecraft constellation.

title: BlackSky Global 5 & 6
location: First Launch Pad, Satish Dhawan Space Centre, India
mission_data.title: BlackSky Global 5 & 6
mission_data.description: BlackSky Global 5 and 6 are part of sixty high resolution earth observation microsatellites in the BlackSky constellation. This constellation will provide real-time earth observation. the constellation is built by Blacksky, a SpaceFlight Subsidiary, and the satellites are produced by LeoStella LLC, a joint venture of Spaceflight Industries and Thales Alenia Space.

title: Skylark 5-8
location: Māhia Peninsula, New Zealand
mission_data.title: Skylark 5-8
mission_data.description: The Skylark satellites, built and operated by Spire, will monitor all near-Earth orbits from space, delivering enhanced Space Situational Awareness services to the global satellite community, with timely and precise information for space object detection, tracking, orbit determination, collision avoidance, navigation, and proximity alerts.

title: Skylark 9-12
location: Māhia Peninsula, New Zealand
mission_data.title: Skylark 9-12
mission_data.description: The Skylark satellites, built and operated by Spire, will monitor all near-Earth orbits from space, delivering enhanced Space Situational Awareness services to the global satellite community, with timely and precise information for space object detection, tracking, orbit determination, collision avoidance, navigation, and proximity alerts.

title: StriX Launch 6
location: Māhia Peninsula, New Zealand
mission_data.title: StriX Launch 6
mission_data.description: This is the second of a bulk buy of two Electron launches by Synspective to deliver their StriX satellites to low Earth orbit. StriX satellites can collect data with a ground resolution of 1-3m and a swath width of more than 10-30km. Each Electron launch will deliver 1 StriX satellite into orbit. This will be the overall 6th StriX satellite launched by Rocket Lab for Synspective.

title: Mangalyaan-2
location: Second Launch Pad, Satish Dhawan Space Centre, India
mission_data.title: Mangalyaan-2
mission_data.description: Mangalyaan-2, also known as Mars Orbiter Mission (MOM) 2, is a planned Mars orbiter following in the footsteps of Mangalyaan-1, which was also a Mars orbiter. The orbiter will use aerobraking to lower its initial apoapsis and enter into an orbit suitable for observations.The mission will include a hyperspectral camera, a high-resolution panchromatic camera, and a radar to understand early Martian crust, recent basalts, and boulder falls.

title: BlackSky Gen-3 Mission 2
location: Māhia Peninsula, New Zealand
mission_data.title: BlackSky Gen-3 Mission 2
mission_data.description: The second of five BlackSky Technology missions to deploy its new next-generation BlackSky Gen-3 satellites. The commercial constellation of Gen-3 satellites has the capability to produce images with 50-centimeter resolution and to host multiple sensors, including shortwave infrared (SWIR). The improved resolution and enhanced spectral diversity of the Gen-3 satellites will expand BlackSky's ability to provide real-time information to its customers.

location: Māhia Peninsula, New Zealand
mission_data.title: BlackSky Gen-3 Mission 3
mission_data.description: The third of five BlackSky Technology missions deploying its new next-generation BlackSky Gen-3 satellites. The commercial constellation of Gen-3 satellites has the capability to produce images with a resolution of 50 centimeters and to host multiple sensors, including shortwave infrared (SWIR). The improved resolution and enhanced spectral diversity of the Gen-3 satellites will expand BlackSky's ability to provide real-time information to its customers.

location: Māhia Peninsula, New Zealand

location: Māhia Peninsula, New Zealand

mission_data.description: BlackSky Technology's fifth and final mission will deploy its new next-generation BlackSky Gen-3 satellites. The commercial constellation of Gen-3 satellites has the capability to produce images with a resolution of 50 centimeters and to host multiple sensors, including shortwave infrared (SWIR). The improved resolution and enhanced spectral diversity of the Gen-3 satellites will expand BlackSky's ability to provide real-time information to its customers.

title: Leidos Mission 2
location: Rocket Lab LC-2 (LP-0C), Wallops Flight Facility, Virginia, USA
mission_data.title: Leidos Mission 2
mission_data.description: MACH-TB is a full-scale test of Leidos' MACH-TB program. The Multi-Service Advanced Capability Hypersonic Test Bed (MACH-TB) program aims to increase the speed of testing of all commercially available hypersonic systems. The program also envisioned the creation of an experimental glide body (EGB) that will allow the team to collect data and validate the performance of hypersonic glide body components.

location: Rocket Lab LC-2 (LP-0C), Wallops Flight Facility, Virginia, USA

title: Acadia Mission 4
location: Māhia Peninsula, NZ or Wallops Flight Facility, USA
mission_data.title: Acadia Mission 4
mission_data.description: Capella Space introduced its latest generation of satellites named "Acadia", which offer increased imaging capability and improved communications connectivity. These satellites are smaller and lighter than previous models, but offer higher resolution and detection capabilities, enabling better Earth observation and more accurate decision-making.

location: Commercial LC-2, Wenchang Space Launch Site, China

title: Owlet-01
description: 3rd launch of RS1, contingent on the success of its upcoming 2nd launch.
location: LP-3C, Pacific Spaceport Complex, Kodiak, Alaska, USA
mission_data.title: Owlet-01
mission_data.description: Based in Reston, Virginia, Scout Space develops optical sensors for space traffic management and other applications. The Owlet is a version of the company’s Owl telescope aimed at military applications in geostationary and cislunar orbits.

title: PRIME-1 (IM-2)
location: LC-39A, Kennedy Space Center, Florida, USA
mission_data.title: PRIME-1
mission_data.description: Intuitive Machines-2 will deliver The Regolith and Ice Drill for Exploring New Terrain (TRIDENT) and the Mass Spectrometer observing lunar operations (MSolo). PRIME-1 will drill into the lunar surface, harvest and bring ice to the Moon’s surface, and use a mass spectrometer to measure how much is lost to sublimation as it turns from solid into vapor in a vacuum. The mission will also carry a deployable lander called Micro Nova (µNova), which will demonstrate the ability to carry a payload of 1kg and travel more than 2.5 km by doing "hops". During the flights, µNova will also provide high-resolution imagery of craters.

title: GPS-3 7
location: SLC-41, Cape Canaveral SFS, Florida, USA
mission_data.title: GPS-3 7
mission_data.description: GPS-3 (Global Positioning System) or Navstar-3 (Navigation System using Timing And Ranging) are the first evolution stage of the third generation of the GPS satellites.

title: Progress MS-30
location: Site 31/6, Baikonur Cosmodrome, Kazakhstan
mission_data.title: Progress MS-30
mission_data.description: Progress (in Russian: "Прогресс") MS-29 is a Russian cargo vehicle which will resupply the International Space Station. This will be the 182nd flight of a Progress.

title: SPHEREx & PUNCH
location: SLC-4E, Vandenberg SFB, California, USA
mission_data.title: SPHEREx
mission_data.description: The Spectro-Photometer for the History of the Universe, Epoch of Reionization and Ices Explorer mission will provide the first all-sky spectral survey. Over a two-year planned mission, the SPHEREx Observatory will collect data on more than 300 million galaxies along with more than 100 million stars in the Milky Way in order to explore the origins of the universe.

title: LOTUSat-1 (Demo Flight)
description: First flight of Epsilon S.
location: Mu Pad, Uchinoura Space Center, Japan
mission_data.title: LOTUSat-1
mission_data.description: Vietnamese Earth observation satellite. NEC Corporation is contracted to construct the satellite. The satellite will contribute to measures against natural disasters and climate change in Vietnam.

title: LOXSAT 1
location: Māhia Peninsula, New Zealand
mission_data.title: LOXSAT 1
mission_data.description: LOXSAT 1 will demonstrate long term storage of cryogenic propellants on orbit as well as fuel transfer experiments.

title: SpaceX Crew-10
location: SLC-40 or LC-39A, Florida, USA
mission_data.title: SpaceX Crew-10
mission_data.description: SpaceX Crew-10 is the tenth operational crewed rotation mission of a Crew Dragon spacecraft to the International Space Station. The crew will be composed of NASA astronauts commander Anne McClain and pilot Nichole Ayes, and mission specialists Takuya Onishi of Japan's JAXA and Kirill Peskov of Russia's Roscosmos. Nichole Ayers will become the first member of NASA’s 2021 astronaut class to launch to orbit.

title: CRS NG-22
description: Due to the retirement of the Antares 230+ rocket, Northrop Grumman purchased three missions from SpaceX to launch the Cygnus spacecraft to the International Space Station before the Antares 330 rocket enters operation and fulfill the CRS Phase 2 contract manifest.
location: SLC-40 or LC-39A, Florida, USA
mission_data.title: CRS NG-22
mission_data.description: Cygnus NG-22 (Northrop Grumman-22) is a cargo resupply mission of the Northrop Grumman Cygnus spacecraft to the International Space Station under the Commercial Resupply Services (CRS) contract with NASA.

title: Transporter 13
location: CCSFS/KSC, Florida or VSFB, California, USA
mission_data.title: Transporter 13
mission_data.description: Transporter 13 is a dedicated rideshare mission by SpaceX. SpaceX’s SmallSat Rideshare Program provides small satellite operators with regularly scheduled, dedicated Falcon 9 rideshare missions to SSO for ESPA class payloads for as low as $300,000 per mission, which includes up to 50kg of payload mass.

title: Kinéis 21-25
location: Māhia Peninsula, New Zealand
mission_data.title: Kinéis 21-25
mission_data.description: Fifth and final batch of five satellites for the French Kinéis IoT constellation designed to operate with 25 nanosatellites of 30 kg each. The constellation will enable Kinéis, a company backed by private and public investors including the French government’s space agency CNES (Centre National d'Études Spatiales) and CLS (Collecte Localisation Satellites) an international space-based solutions provider, to improve its global IoT connectivity.

title: Bandwagon-3
location: CCSFS/KSC, Florida or VSFB, California, USA
mission_data.title: Bandwagon-3
mission_data.description: Bandwagon-3 is a dedicated rideshare mission by SpaceX. SpaceX’s SmallSat Rideshare Program provides small satellite operators with regularly scheduled, dedicated Falcon 9 rideshare missions to mid-inclination orbits for ESPA class payloads for as low as $300,000 per mission, which includes up to 50kg of payload mass.

title: Sentinel-3C
location: ELV, Guiana Space Centre, French Guiana, France
mission_data.title: Sentinel-3C
mission_data.description: Sentinel-3C is an Earth observation satellite constellation developed by the European Space Agency as part of the Copernicus Programme.Copernicus, formerly Global Monitoring for Environment and Security, is the European programme to establish a European capacity for Earth observation designed to provide European policymakers and public authorities with accurate and timely information to better manage the environment and to understand and mitigate the effects of climate change.

title: MRV-1
location: SLC-40 or LC-39A, Florida, USA
mission_data.title: MRV-1
mission_data.description: MRV (Mission Robotic Vehicle) is a satellite servicing payload being built by the Northrop Grumman owned company SpaceLogistics. It designed to attach up to 30 MEPs (Mission Extension Pods) to satellites in GEO over the course of its life.

title: Pathfinder Mission 1
location: LC-36, Cape Canaveral SFS, Florida, USA
mission_data.title: Pathfinder Mission 1
mission_data.description: Pathfinder Mission 1 or MK1-SN001 is the first of two test missions to validate the technologies needed for its HLS lunar module, some of the life support hardware will travel on this mission in preparation for the first manned flight. MK1-SN001 proves out critical systems, including the BE-7 engine, cryogenic fluid power and propulsions systems, avionics, continuous downlink communications, and precision landing.

title: DART AE
description: Part of Rocket Lab's HASTE Program.
location: Rocket Lab LC-2 (LP-0C), Wallops Flight Facility, Virginia, USA
mission_data.title: DART AE
mission_data.description: DART AE, produced by Hypersonix, is a three-metre-long, single-use, high-temperature alloy, hydrogen-fuelled, scramjet technology demonstrator. DART AE (Additive Engineering) makes significant use of 3D printing and is powered by a single patented 3D printed SPARTAN scramjet engine.

title: Soyuz MS-27
location: Site 31/6, Baikonur Cosmodrome, Kazakhstan
mission_data.title: Soyuz MS-27
mission_data.description: Soyuz MS-27 is a crewed mission to the International Space Station. The crew consists of Roscosmos cosmonauts Sergey Ryzhikov, Alexey Zubritsky, and NASA astronaut Jonathan "Jonny" Kim. The trio will spend around eight months at the space station, and this will be Kim's first space station mission.

title: NISAR
location: Second Launch Pad, Satish Dhawan Space Centre, India
mission_data.title: NISAR
mission_data.description: The NASA-ISRO Synthetic Aperture Radar, or NISAR satellite, will use advanced radar imaging to map the elevation of Earth's land and ice masses 4 to 6 times a month at resolutions of 5 to 10 meters. It is designed to observe and measure some of the planet's most complex natural processes, including ecosystem disturbances, ice-sheet collapse, and natural hazards such as earthquakes, tsunamis, volcanoes and landslides.

title: IMAP
location: SLC-40, Cape Canaveral SFS, Florida, USA
mission_data.title: IMAP
mission_data.description: Interstellar Mapping and Acceleration Probe (IMAP) will help researchers better understand the boundary of the heliosphere, a magnetic barrier surrounding our solar system. This region is where the constant flow of particles from our Sun, called the solar wind, collides with winds from other stars. This collision limits the amount of harmful cosmic radiation entering the heliosphere. IMAP will collect and map neutral particles that make it through, as well as investigate the fundamental processes of how particles are accelerated in space, from its vantage point orbiting the Sun at the Lagrange 1 point directly between the Sun and Earth.

title: Axiom Mission 4 (Ax-4)
location: SLC-40 or LC-39A, Florida, USA
mission_data.title: Axiom Mission 4 (Ax-4)
mission_data.description: Ax-4 is Axiom Space's fourth private crew rotation to the International Space Station aboard a SpaceX Crew Dragon spacecraft. The crew will be composed of commander Peggy Whitson (former NASA astronaut), Shubhanshu Shukla of India, Sławosz Uznański of Poland, and Tibor Kapu of Hungary. This will be India and Poland's first crewed trip to the ISS.

title: STP-S29B
location: SLC-46, Cape Canaveral SFS, Florida, USA
mission_data.title: STP-S29B
mission_data.description: The STP-S29B mission will provide orbital launch services for the DoD STP. The DoD STP furthers the maturation of space-based warfighter technologies across the DoD enterprise by providing space access solutions for all research and development-related DoD auxiliary payloads on DoD, civil and commercial launches and for all non-DoD auxiliary payloads seeking launch opportunities on DoD missions.

title: Tianwen 2
description: First Chinese mission to return asteroid samples.
location: Xichang Satellite Launch Center, China
mission_data.title: Tianwen 2
mission_data.description: The Tianwen 2 near-Earth asteroid sample return mission, previously named "Zheng He" after the 15th-century naval explorer and admiral, will target near-Earth asteroid 469219 Kamoʻoalewa (2016 HO3), collecting about 1000 grams of samples from its surface using both touch-and-go and anchor-and-drill approaches. The samples will be returned to Earth about 2.5 years of launch.

title: Shenzhou 20
location: Site 901 (SLS-1), Jiuquan Satellite Launch Center, China
mission_data.title: Shenzhou 20
mission_data.description: Shenzhou 20 (Chinese: 神舟二十号), the flight will mark the 15th crewed Chinese spaceflight and the twentieth flight of the Shenzhou program. The spacecraft will carry three People's Liberation Army Astronaut Corps (PLAAC) taikonauts on the ninth flight to the Tianhe core module, the first module of the Tiangong space station.

title: EWS-OD 1
location: SLC-8, Vandenberg SFB, California, USA
mission_data.title: EWS-OD 1
mission_data.description: EWS-OD 1 or EWS Operational Demonstration-1, integrate the EWS payload and provide on-orbit mission control services to support the collection of theater weather imagery and cloud characterization data for worldwide military operational use.

title: TSIS-2
location: SLC-40 or LC-39A, Florida, USA
mission_data.title: TSIS-2
mission_data.description: NASA's Total and Spectral Solar Irradiance Sensor – 2, or TSIS-2, will measure the Sun's energy input to Earth. Since 1978, various satellites have measured the Sun’s brightness above Earth’s atmosphere. TSIS-2 will add solar irradiance measurements to four decades of continuous data records. Unlike its predecessor TSIS-1, which operates from the International Space Station, TSIS-2 will ride on a free-flying spacecraft.

title: Bandwagon-4
location: CCSFS/KSC, Florida or VSFB, California, USA
mission_data.title: Bandwagon-4
mission_data.description: Bandwagon-4 is a dedicated rideshare mission by SpaceX. SpaceX’s SmallSat Rideshare Program provides small satellite operators with regularly scheduled, dedicated Falcon 9 rideshare missions to mid-inclination orbits for ESPA class payloads for as low as $300,000 per mission, which includes up to 50kg of payload mass.

title: ViaSat-3 Asia-Pacific
description: In late April 2023, it was announced that Viasat Asia-Pacific will no longer fly on Ariane 6, due to delays in Ariane 6 development as well as the re-manifestation of several payloads from Russian launchers to Ariane vehicles after Russia invaded Ukraine. Viasat is currently evaluating other launch vehicles for this launch. We will keep the rocket set to the Ariane 64 until Viasat re-manifests its satellite onto a different launcher.
location: ELA-4, Guiana Space Centre, French Guiana, France
mission_data.title: ViaSat-3 APAC (Asia-Pacific)
mission_data.description: The ViaSat-3 class of Ka-band satellites is expected to provide unprecedented capabilities in terms of service speed and flexibility for a satellite platform. The first two satellites will focus on the Americas and on Europe, the Middle East, and Africa (EMEA), respectively, with the third satellite planned for the APAC region, completing Viasat's global service coverage. Each ViaSat-3 class satellite is expected to deliver more than 1 terabit per second of network capacity and to leverage high levels of flexibility to dynamically direct capacity to where customers are located.

title: METOP-SG A1
location: ELA-4, Guiana Space Centre, French Guiana, France
mission_data.title: METOP-SG A1
mission_data.description: METOP-SG (Meteorological Operational - Second Generation) is Europe's second-generation polar-orbiting operational meteorological satellite system to replace the first-generation METOP satellites.

title: SPAINSAT New Generation II
location: SLC-40 or LC-39A, Florida, USA
mission_data.title: SPAINSAT New Generation II
mission_data.description: SPAINSAT NG is Hisdesat's largest project since its foundation. Its technological complexity and strategic relevance will position the company as an international benchmark in satellite communications. The new Spainsat NG generation will multiply by 16 times the capacity in X and Ka military band with respect to the current devices and will add a new payload in UHF band. In addition, it will operate with active X-band antennas in receive and transmit. Pioneers in the European aerospace sector, each of them will be assigned 16 different areas of operation to perform their coverage services with electronic configuration.

location: CCSFS/KSC, Florida or VSFB, California, USA
mission_data.title: Project Kuiper
mission_data.description: Project Kuiper is a mega constellation of satellites in Low Earth Orbit that will offer broadband internet access, this constellation will be managed by Kuiper Systems LLC, a subsidiary of Amazon. This constellation is planned to be composed of 3,276 satellites. The satellites are projected to be placed in 98 orbital planes in three orbital layers, one at 590 km, 610 km and 630 km altitude.

title: MTG-S1/Sentinel-4A
location: SLC-40 or LC-39A, Florida, USA
mission_data.title: MTG-S1/Sentinel-4A
mission_data.description: MTG (Meteosat Third Generation) is the follow-up system to the Meteosat MSG series of geostationary satellites.

title: ESCAPADE
location: LC-36, Cape Canaveral SFS, Florida, USA
mission_data.title: ESCAPADE
mission_data.description: The Escape and Plasma Acceleration and Dynamics Explorers (EscaPADE) are a dual-spacecraft mission to study ion and sputtered escape from Mars. The two identical spacecraft were scheduled for launch as secondary satellites on the Psyche mission in August 2022 but were removed due to problems with the required trajectory. The science goals of the mission are to: understand the processes controlling the structure of Mars' hybrid magnetosphere and how it guides ion flows; understand how energy and momentum are transported from the solar wind through Mars' magnetosphere; and understand the processes controlling the flow of energy and matter into and out of the collisional atmosphere. EscaPADE is part of the NASA Small Innovative Missions for Planetary Exploration (SIMPLEx) program.

title: GSAT-32 (GSAT-N3)
location: Second Launch Pad, Satish Dhawan Space Centre, India
mission_data.title: GSAT-32 (GSAT-N3)
mission_data.description: GSAT-32 is a communications satellites for the Indian space agency, ISRO. The spacecraft is a replacement for GSAT-6 which will be near its end-of-life by the end of 2024.

title: CAS500-3
location: LC-2, Naro Space Center, South Korea
mission_data.title: CAS500-3
mission_data.description: The South Korean CAS500-3 (Compact Advanced Satellite 500 3) is a technology verification Earth-observation satellite.

title: Starliner-1
location: SLC-41, Cape Canaveral SFS, Florida, USA
mission_data.title: Starliner-1
mission_data.description: Starliner-1 is the first operational crew rotation mission of Boeing's Starliner spacecraft to the International Space Station. The crew will consist of NASA astronauts Scott Tingle as commander, Michael Fincke as pilot and Canadian astronaut Joshua Kutryk. Other crew members are still yet to be announced.

title: CRS NG-23
description: First mission of the Antares 330 rocket, an improved version of the Antares 230 which has a first stage developed by Northrop Grumman and Firefly Aerospace.
location: LP-0A, Wallops Flight Facility, Virginia, USA
mission_data.title: CRS NG-23
mission_data.description: Cygnus NG-23 (Northrop Grumman-23) is a cargo resupply mission of the Northrop Grumman Cygnus spacecraft to the International Space Station under the Commercial Resupply Services (CRS) contract with NASA.

title: Haven-1
location: SLC-40 or LC-39A, Florida, USA
mission_data.title: Haven-1
mission_data.description: Haven-1 will act as an independent crewed space station. The station will have an active mission length of up to 3 years and support up to 4 crewed missions, each lasting 10 days and carrying 4 crew members.

title: Maiden flight
description: Maiden flight of CAS Space's Kinetica-2 rocket.
location: Jiuquan Satellite Launch Center, China

title: Artemis II
description: First crewed flight of the Orion spacecraft. First time humans will go beyond Low Earth Orbit since Apollo 17 in 1972.
location: LC-39B, Kennedy Space Center, Florida, USA
mission_data.title: Artemis II
mission_data.description: Artemis II mission plan is to send four astronauts in the first crewed Orion capsule into a lunar free return trajectory for a 10 day mission. The mission will include the first non-American, Canadian specifically, and likely the first woman to leave low earth orbit. Because of the hydrogen boil-off due to the increased time spent in a LEO parking orbit compared to Artemis I, the mission will use a multi-translunar injection (MTLI), or multiple departure burns to preform the translunar injection burn. The burn will be partially completed by the ICPS 2nd stage before being fully completed by the European Service Module (ESM) on the following orbit.

title: KOMPSAT-7A
location: SLC-40 or LC-39A, Florida, USA
mission_data.title: KOMPSAT-7A
mission_data.description: KOMPSAT 7A (Korean Multi-purpose Satellite 7A) is a lightweight Earth observation satellite developed by the Korea Aerospace Research Institute.

title: CRS SNC-2
location: SLC-41, Cape Canaveral SFS, Florida, USA
mission_data.title: CRS SNC-2
mission_data.description: The Dream Chaser Cargo System is an American reusable spaceplane being developed by Sierra Nevada Corporation (SNC) Space Systems. The Dream Chaser is designed to resupply the International Space Station with both pressurized and unpressurized cargo. The vehicle will launch vertically and autonomously land horizontally on conventional runways.

title: Gateway PPE & HALO
description: Falcon Heavy will be equipped with an extended payload fairing for this launch.
location: LC-39A, Kennedy Space Center, Florida, USA
mission_data.title: PPE & HALO
mission_data.description: NASA has selected SpaceX to provide launch services for the agency’s Power and Propulsion Element (PPE) and Habitation and Logistics Outpost (HALO), the foundational elements of the Gateway. As the first long-term orbiting outpost around the Moon, the Gateway is critical to supporting sustainable astronauts missions under the agency’s Artemis program.

title: Transporter 15
location: CCSFS/KSC, Florida or VSFB, California, USA
mission_data.title: Transporter 15
mission_data.description: Transporter 15 is a dedicated rideshare mission by SpaceX. SpaceX’s SmallSat Rideshare Program provides small satellite operators with regularly scheduled, dedicated Falcon 9 rideshare missions to SSO for ESPA class payloads for as low as $300,000 per mission, which includes up to 50kg of payload mass.

title: Space Rider F1
location: ELV, Guiana Space Centre, French Guiana, France
mission_data.title: Space Rider
mission_data.description: Space Rider is a reusable lifting-body orbital and re-entry experiment, which aims to provide Europe with an affordable, independent, reusable end-to-end integrated space transportation system for routine access and return from low orbit. It will be used to transport payloads for an array of applications, orbit altitudes, and inclinations.

title: GaganYaan Crewed Flight
description: First Indian crewed flight. India will become the fourth space power in history to have launched a crew into space, after the Soviet Union, the USA and China.
location: Second Launch Pad, Satish Dhawan Space Centre, India
mission_data.title: GaganYaan Crewed Flight
mission_data.description: The purpose of the mission is to demonstrate the ability of the GaganYaan spacecraft to carry humans into low earth orbit.

title: EDRS-D
location: ELA-4, Guiana Space Centre, French Guiana, France
mission_data.title: EDRS-D
mission_data.description: The EDRS’s two telecommunication payloads in geostationary orbit will enable broadband, bi-directional data relay between Low Earth Orbit (LEO) satellites and an associated ground segment via either of the EDRS payloads. The EDRS increases the time LEO spacecraft can be in communication with the ground and enables immediate broadband data transfer to the user. It also provides the capability to re-programme LEO Earth observation (EO) satellites in almost real-time. This ensures the timely acquisition and delivery of imagery following natural disasters and helps emergency services on the ground to accurately map the affected areas and effectively coordinate response efforts. Currently, LEO satellites can only be reprogrammed and images can only be received when the satellites pass over a specific geographic location with a dedicated ground station.

title: SMILE
location: ELV, Guiana Space Centre, French Guiana, France
mission_data.title: SMILE
mission_data.description: Solar wind Magnetosphere Ionosphere Link Explorer (SMILE) is a planned joint venture mission between the European Space Agency and the Chinese Academy of Sciences. SMILE will image for the first time the magnetosphere in soft X-rays and UV during up to 40 hours per orbit, improving our understanding of the dynamic interaction between the solar wind and Earth's magnetosphere.

title: Galileo FOC FM29-FM30
location: ELA-4, Guiana Space Centre, French Guiana, France
mission_data.title: Galileo FOC FM29-FM30
mission_data.description: Galileo is the global navigation satellite system (GNSS) that went live in 2016, created by the European Union (EU) through the European GNSS Agency (GSA), headquartered in Prague in the Czech Republic, with two ground operations centers, Oberpfaffenhofen near Munich in Germany and Fucino in Italy. The project is named after the Italian astronomer Galileo Galilei. One of the aims of Galileo is to provide an independent high-precision positioning system so European nations do not have to rely on the U.S. GPS, or the Russian GLONASS systems, which could be disabled or degraded by their operators at any time.

location: Site 31/6, Baikonur Cosmodrome, Kazakhstan
mission_data.title: Arktika-M n°3
mission_data.description: Arktika-M is a series of planned Russian remote-sensing and emergency communications satellites operating in an highly elliptical 12-hour orbit. The constellation of two Aktika-M satellites is designed to monitor high-latitude areas of the Earth. The spacecraft will be based on Lavochkin's Elektro-L meteorological satellite.

location: Site 81/24, Baikonur Cosmodrome, Kazakhstan
mission_data.title: Elektro-L n°5
mission_data.description: Elektro-L n°5 is a Russian geostationary weather satellite. It is the fifth Elektro-L spacecraft to fly. It replaces the first Elektro series, which was never brought to operational service. The Elektro-L satellites are based on Lavochkins Navigator-Bus. Elektro-L also features receivers for the SARSAT-COSPAS emergency call system.

mission_data.description: QZSS (Quasi Zenith Satellite System) is a Japanese satellite navigation system operating from inclined, elliptical geosynchronous orbits to achieve optimal high-elevation visibility in urban canyons and mountainous areas. The navigation system objective is to broadcast GPS-interoperable and augmentation signals as well as original Japanese (QZSS) signals from a three-spacecraft constellation.

mission_data.description: The Lunar Polar Exploration mission (LUPEX) is a robotic lunar mission jointly developed by the Indian Space Research Organisation (ISRO) and Japan Aerospace Exploration Agency (JAXA), deploying a lunar rover and lander to explore the south pole region of the Moon.

title: DESTINY+
location: Mu Pad, Uchinoura Space Center, Japan
mission_data.title: DESTINY+
mission_data.description: DESTINY+ (Demonstration and Experiment of Space Technology for INterplanetary voYage with Phaethon fLyby and dUst Science) is a planned asteroid exploration mission to 3200 Phaethon, the parent body of the Geminids meteor shower. It will demonstrate further improvements of low cost solar electric propulsion in deep space and innovative light-weight solar array panel technology.

location: Mu Pad, Uchinoura Space Center, Japan
mission_data.title: RAISE-4
mission_data.description: RAISE-4 (RApid Innovative payload demonstration Satellite-4) is a satellite for on-orbit demonstrations of 15 demonstration components and equipment selected by public solicitation. The satellite will be operated in response to requests from the demonstration theme proposers, and will provide experimental data of the demonstration devices and environmental data during the experiments.

title: IRIDE Mission 1
location: ELV, Guiana Space Centre, French Guiana, France
mission_data.title: IRIDE Mission 1
mission_data.description: IRIDE is an end-to-end system composed of constellations of LEO satellites (Upstream Segment), the ground-based Operations infrastructure (Downstream Segment), and a range of Services to be delivered to the Italian Public Administration (Service Segment). The constellation will be based on different sensing techniques and technologies, encompassing Synthetic Aperture Radars, SAR, imaging as well as optical imaging, from medium to high resolution and in many different frequency ranges.

title: MicroCarb
location: ELV, Guiana Space Centre, French Guiana, France
mission_data.title: MicroCarb
mission_data.description: MicroCarb is a small satellite designed to map sources and sinks of carbon dioxide (CO2)—the most important greenhouse gas — on a global scale. MicroCarb's dispersive spectrometer instrument will be able to measure atmospheric concentration of CO2 globally with a high degree of precision (on the order of 1 ppm) and with a pixel size of 4.5 km x 9 km.

mission_data.title: GaganYaan Demo Flight 3
mission_data.description: The mission is the third uncrewed test flight of ISRO's GaganYaan human-rated capsule into orbit.

title: Griffin Mission One
location: LC-39A, Kennedy Space Center, Florida, USA
mission_data.title: Griffin Mission One
mission_data.description: Astrobotic's Griffin lander is a lunar lander contracted by NASA as part of the Commercial Lunar Payloads Services (CLPS) program. Multiple scientific payloads will likely be included on Griffin's exterior. VIPER was previously planned as a primary payload on the Griffin lander before the VIPER project was discontinued.

title: PRISM (IM-3)
location: LC-39A, Kennedy Space Center, Florida, USA
mission_data.title: PRISM (IM-3)
mission_data.description: The IM-3 mission includes a Nova-C class lander to land 130kg of payloads on the lunar surface. It also has excess capacity on the launch vehicle that accommodates 1000kg of payloads on a rideshare dispenser ring that deploys into a lunar transfer orbit. Intuitive Machines’ “rideshare” option puts customers in a high-energy orbit to efficiently proceed to lunar capture, redirect to points elsewhere in high Earth orbit, or depart for destinations in the solar system.

title: CHORUS
location: SLC-40 or LC-39A, Florida, USA
mission_data.title: CHORUS
mission_data.description: CHORUS is MDA's next generation Earth observation constellation, consisting of 2 radar satellites (, C-band SAR and X-band SAR), in a 53.5 degree 600 km altitude LEO, with the X-band trailing the C-band by 60 minutes. A collaborative multi-sensor constellation, CHORUS will bring together diverse and unique imagery and data sources and provide a new level of near real-time insight and innovative Earth observation services. Operating in a unique mid-inclination orbit, CHORUS will be able to image day or night, regardless of weather conditions, with daily access of up to 95% of the coverage area. From an industry-leading 700km-wide imaging swath down to sub-metre high resolution, CHORUS will provide the most extensive and unrivalled Earth observation radar imaging capacity available on the market in a single mission.

title: CRS SNC-3
location: SLC-41, Cape Canaveral SFS, Florida, USA
mission_data.title: CRS SNC-3
mission_data.description: The Dream Chaser Cargo System is an American reusable spaceplane being developed by Sierra Nevada Corporation (SNC) Space Systems. The Dream Chaser is designed to resupply the International Space Station with both pressurized and unpressurized cargo. The vehicle will launch vertically and autonomously land horizontally on conventional runways.

title: Galileo FOC FM28 & FM31
location: ELA-4, Guiana Space Centre, French Guiana, France
mission_data.title: Galileo FOC FM28 & FM31
mission_data.description: Galileo is the global navigation satellite system (GNSS) that went live in 2016, created by the European Union (EU) through the European GNSS Agency (GSA), headquartered in Prague in the Czech Republic, with two ground operations centers, Oberpfaffenhofen near Munich in Germany and Fucino in Italy. The project is named after the Italian astronomer Galileo Galilei. One of the aims of Galileo is to provide an independent high-precision positioning system so European nations do not have to rely on the U.S. GPS, or the Russian GLONASS systems, which could be disabled or degraded by their operators at any time.

title: KOMPSAT-6
description: The launch of this mission was originally planned with Roscosmos' Angara 1.2 rocket, but the South Korean Ministry of Science cancelled this contract due to sanctions against Russia and signed a launch contract with Arianespace.
location: ELV, Guiana Space Centre, French Guiana, France
mission_data.title: KOMPSAT-6
mission_data.description: KOMPSAT-6 (acronym for KOrean Multi-Purpose SATellite-6), also called Arirang-6 (in Korean 아리랑 6 호), is the sixth South Korean Earth observation satellite in the KOMPSAT series. Its payload consists of a synthetic aperture radar providing images with a resolution power of between 0.5 meters and 20 meters depending on the modes.

title: VICTUS HAZE
location: Māhia Peninsula, New Zealand
mission_data.title: VICTUS HAZE
mission_data.description: VICTUS HAZE will see Rocket Lab design, build, launch, and operate a rendezvous proximity operation (RPO) capable spacecraft. SSC’s Space Safari’s VICTUS HAZE mission will be an exercise of a realistic threat-response scenario and on-orbit space domain awareness (SDA) demonstration. Once the spacecraft build is complete, Rocket Lab will be entered into a Hot Standby Phase awaiting further direction. Once the exercise begins, Rocket Lab will be given notice to launch the spacecraft into a target orbit. After reaching orbit, the spacecraft will be rapidly commissioned and readied for operations. Rocket Lab will configure a Pioneer class spacecraft bus to meet the unique requirements of the VICTUS HAZE mission.

mission_data.description: This is the first of a bulk buy of 10 Electron launches by Synspective to deliver their StriX satellites to low Earth orbit. StriX satellites can collect data with a ground resolution of 1-3m and a swath width of more than 10-30km. Each Electron launch will deliver 1 StriX satellite into orbit. This will be the overall 7th StriX satellite launched by Rocket Lab for Synspective.

title: Transporter 16
location: CCSFS/KSC, Florida or VSFB, California, USA
mission_data.title: Transporter 16
mission_data.description: Transporter 16 is a dedicated rideshare mission by SpaceX. SpaceX’s SmallSat Rideshare Program provides small satellite operators with regularly scheduled, dedicated Falcon 9 rideshare missions to SSO for ESPA class payloads for as low as $300,000 per mission, which includes up to 50kg of payload mass.

title: METOP-SG B1
location: ELA-4, Guiana Space Centre, French Guiana, France
mission_data.title: METOP-SG B1
mission_data.description: METOP-SG (Meteorological Operational - Second Generation) is Europe's second-generation polar-orbiting operational meteorological satellite system to replace the first-generation METOP satellites.

title: STP-S30
location: Rocket Lab LC-2 (LP-0C), Wallops Flight Facility, Virginia, USA
mission_data.title: STP-S30
mission_data.description: STP-S30 is a complex mission that will deliver research experiments and technology demonstrations to orbit for the DoD and contribute to future space systems development. The projected primary payload, DISKSat, will demonstrate sustained very low earth orbit (VLEO) flight and test a unique, 1-meter diameter, disk-shaped satellite bus that is designed to increase on-orbit persistence.

title: Astrolab Mission 1
location: LC-39A Starship Pad, Kennedy Space Center, Florida, USA
mission_data.title: Astrolab Mission 1
mission_data.description: Astrolab, a lunar rover developer, has signed an agreement with SpaceX to send its first rover to the moon on a future Starship flight. The rover, named FLEX (Flexible Logistics and Exploration), will be part of a payload on a Starship lunar lander mission scheduled for around mid-2026. This marks SpaceX's first commercial contract for lunar cargo delivery.

title: Intelsat IS-45
location: ELA-4, Guiana Space Centre, French Guiana, France
mission_data.title: Intelsat IS-45
mission_data.description: Intelsat 45 is a small geostationary communications satellite that will provide Ku-band fixed-satellite services enabling Intelsat to provide specialized and efficient service to Media and Network customers. IS-45 weighs about 1 metric ton at launch and is designed and built by SWISSto12, based on the company’s innovative HummingSat platform.

title: Transporter 17
location: CCSFS/KSC, Florida or VSFB, California, USA
mission_data.title: Transporter 17
mission_data.description: Transporter 17 is a dedicated rideshare mission by SpaceX. SpaceX’s SmallSat Rideshare Program provides small satellite operators with regularly scheduled, dedicated Falcon 9 rideshare missions to SSO for ESPA class payloads for as low as $300,000 per mission, which includes up to 50kg of payload mass.

title: ClearSpace 1
location: ELV, Guiana Space Centre, French Guiana, France
mission_data.title: ClearSpace 1
mission_data.description: ClearSpace is a company that intends to remove space debris from orbit. This first flight aims to deorbit a flight adapter from the Vega launcher, left in orbit from the Proba-V mission (VV-05).

title: Artemis III
description: NASA's first crewed lunar landing attempt since Apollo 17 in 1972. Final flight of SLS Block 1.
location: LC-39B, Kennedy Space Center, Florida, USA
mission_data.title: Artemis III
mission_data.description: Artemis III will see 4 unannounced crew members launching to the moon aboard an SLS rocket. From there, they will enter a near-rectilinear-halo-orbit or NRHO. Two crew members will then board a commercial lunar lander, currently planned to be a SpaceX Lunar Starship, and conduct the first crewed lunar landing in over 50 years, while the remaining two crew members will stay aboard Orion. After a two week stay at the Lunar South Pole, the two astronauts will return to Orion and return home.

title: PLATO (Exoplanet Telescope)
location: ELA-4, Guiana Space Centre, French Guiana, France
mission_data.title: PLATO (Exoplanet Telescope)
mission_data.description: PLAnetary Transits and Oscillations of stars (PLATO) is a space telescope under development by the European Space Agency. The mission goals are to search for planetary transits across up to one million stars and to discover and characterize rocky extrasolar planets around yellow dwarf stars (like our sun), subgiant stars, and red dwarf stars. The emphasis of the mission is on Earth-like planets in the habitable zone around sun-like stars where water can exist in a liquid state. It is the third medium-class mission in ESA's Cosmic Vision programme and is named after the influential Greek philosopher Plato, the founding figure of Western philosophy, science, and mathematics. A secondary objective of the mission is to study stellar oscillations or seismic activity in stars to measure stellar masses and evolution and to enable the precise characterization of the planet's host star, including its age.

title: Crewed Lunar Demo
description: First manned landing on the Moon since the end of NASA's Apollo program in 1973.
location: LC-39A Starship Pad, Kennedy Space Center, Florida, USA
mission_data.title: HLS Crewed Lunar Demo
mission_data.description: HLS Crewed Lunar Demo is the second of two missions contracted by NASA to SpaceX. It will be carried out by Starship HLS under the Artemis Program. HLS will be launched to low-earth orbit, where it will dock with and refuel from a Starship propellant depot. From there it will undock and perform a trans-lunar injection burn and enter NRHO (Near-rectilinear halo orbit). It will loiter until an Orion spacecraft crewed with four astronauts as part of the Artemis III mission arrive, at which point the two spacecraft will dock, two astronauts will transfer into Starship HLS, undock again and descend to the Lunar surface. The two astronauts will spend several days on the surface, after which HLS will lift off, rendezvous and dock with Orion once more, completing its mission.

title: Impulse Space's Mars Mission
location: LC-16, Cape Canaveral SFS, Florida, USA
mission_data.title: Impulse Space's Mars Mission
mission_data.description: The integrated Cruise Vehicle, Entry Capsule, and Mars Lander developed by Impulse Space will launch in 2026 on the Relativity Terran R launch vehicle. After traveling through interplanetary space for over half a year, the Cruise Vehicle will inject the Entry Capsule into the correct landing trajectory and detach. The Entry Capsule will use the proven combination of heatshield and parachute to slow down enough to safely deploy the Mars Lander into freefall. The lander will then perform a propulsive landing using purpose-built engines developed in-house at Impulse Space, completing the first commercial payload delivery to the surface of another planet.

title: Sentinel-6B
location: SLC-4E, Vandenberg SFB, California, USA
mission_data.title: Sentinel-6B
mission_data.description: Sentinel-6B aims to continue high-precision ocean altimetry measurements in the 2020–2030 time-frame using two successive, identical satellites, Jason-CS-A and Jason-CS-B.

title: Space Rider F2
location: ELV, Guiana Space Centre, French Guiana, France
mission_data.title: Space Rider
mission_data.description: Space Rider is a reusable lifting-body orbital and re-entry experiment, which aims to provide Europe with an affordable, independent, reusable end-to-end integrated space transportation system for routine access and return from low orbit. It will be used to transport payloads for an array of applications, orbit altitudes, and inclinations.

title: KOMPSAT-7
location: ELV, Guiana Space Centre, French Guiana, France
mission_data.title: KOMPSAT-7
mission_data.description: KOMPSAT 7 (Korean Multi-purpose Satellite 7) is a lightweight Earth observation satellite developed by the Korea Aerospace Research Institute.

location: ELD, Guiana Space Centre, French Guiana, France

title: Ekspress-AMU4
location: Site 200/39, Baikonur Cosmodrome, Kazakhstan
mission_data.title: Ekspress-AMU4
mission_data.description: Russian communication satellite. Due to sanctions, it will be made entirely of Russian components, based on the Express-1000N platform. The intended lifespan of the satellite is at least 15 years.

title: NEM-1
location: Site 1A, Vostochny Cosmodrome, Russia
mission_data.title: NEM-1
mission_data.description: The Science and Power Module, NEM, (industrial designation 371KK63) should become the most advanced component joining the Russian segment of the International Space Station. As its name implies, it will carry state-of-the-art laboratory facilities and large power-generating solar arrays. NEM will also will also provide additional living quarters and new flight control systems. The module could also serve as a cornerstone of a future Russian space station and a deep-space outpost.

title: Galileo FOC FM37-FM38
location: ELA-4, Guiana Space Centre, French Guiana, France
mission_data.title: Galileo FOC FM37-FM38
mission_data.description: Galileo is the global navigation satellite system (GNSS) that went live in 2016, created by the European Union (EU) through the European GNSS Agency (GSA), headquartered in Prague in the Czech Republic, with two ground operations centers, Oberpfaffenhofen near Munich in Germany and Fucino in Italy. The project is named after the Italian astronomer Galileo Galilei. One of the aims of Galileo is to provide an independent high-precision positioning system so European nations do not have to rely on the U.S. GPS, or the Russian GLONASS systems, which could be disabled or degraded by their operators at any time.

title: Boomerang Phobos Mission
location: Site 1S, Vostochny Cosmodrome, Russia
mission_data.title: Boomerang Phobos Mission
mission_data.description: Boomerang is a Russian scientific mission to collect samples from the surface of Phobos and bring them back to Earth.

title: Martian Moon eXplorer (MMX)
description: First Japanese sample return mission from Phobos. First French/German rover.
location: LA-Y2, Tanegashima Space Center, Japan
mission_data.title: Martian Moon eXplorer (MMX)
mission_data.description: MMX is a Japanese scientific mission to land on Phobos, one of the two moons of Mars, to collect samples before bringing them back to Earth.A small French rover, built in cooperation with Germany, will also be embarked on the mission and should be able to explore the moon's surface.

title: Chang'e 7
location: LC-101, Wenchang Space Launch Site, China
mission_data.title: Chang'e 7
mission_data.description: Chang'e 7/CE-7 is scheduled to launch in 2026, including an orbiter, a lander, a mini-hopping probe, and a rover. The mission will land in the South Pole regions of the Moon to study lunar surface environment around the South Pole, especially in looking for water ice in lunar soil.

title: Arktika-M n°4
location: Site 31/6, Baikonur Cosmodrome, Kazakhstan
mission_data.title: Arktika-M n°4
mission_data.description: Arktika-M is a series of planned Russian remote-sensing and emergency communications satellites operating in an highly elliptical 12-hour orbit. The constellation of two Aktika-M satellites is designed to monitor high-latitude areas of the Earth. The spacecraft will be based on Lavochkin's Elektro-L meteorological satellite.

title: VCLS Demo-2R
location: LC-16, Cape Canaveral SFS, Florida, USA
mission_data.title: VCLS Demo-2R
mission_data.description: Venture Class Launch Services Demonstration 2 (VCLS Demo 2) mission to launch small satellites (SmallSats) to space, including CubeSats, microsats or nanosatellites.

title: Arabsat 7A
location: SLC-40 or LC-39A, Florida, USA
mission_data.title: Arabsat 7A
mission_data.description: The Arabsat 7A satellite is the first Arabsat 7th generation satellite and is considered one of the latest satellite technologies in terms of manufacturing, payload, efficiency of performance, and coverage flexibility.Arabsat 7A will be based on the Space-Inspire (INstant SPace In-orbit REconfiguration) innovative product line allowing seamless telecommunications mission and services reconfiguration, instant in-orbit adjustment to broadband connectivity demand, and superior video broadcasting performance while maximizing the effective use of the satellite resources.

title: CRS NG-25
location: LP-0A, Wallops Flight Facility, Virginia, USA
mission_data.title: CRS NG-25
mission_data.description: Cygnus NG-25 (Northrop Grumman-25) is a cargo resupply mission of the Northrop Grumman Cygnus spacecraft to the International Space Station under the Commercial Resupply Services (CRS) contract with NASA.

title: HTV-X 3
location: LA-Y2, Tanegashima Space Center, Japan
mission_data.title: HTV-X 3
mission_data.description: HTV-X is an uncrewed expendable cargo spacecraft under development by Japan Aerospace Exploration Agency (JAXA) as the successor of H-II Transfer Vehicle (HTV), designed to be more affordable than its predecessor, with more pressurized cargo capability and cargo late load options.

title: Uncrewed Lunar Demo
location: LC-39A Starship Pad, Kennedy Space Center, Florida, USA
mission_data.title: HLS Uncrewed Lunar Demo
mission_data.description: HLS Uncewed Lunar Demo is the first of two missions contracted by NASA to SpaceX. It will be carried out by Starship HLS under the Artemis Program. HLS will be launched to low-earth orbit, where it will dock with and refuel from a Starship propellant depot. From there it will undock and perform a trans-lunar injection burn and enter NRHO (Near-rectilinear halo orbit). From here it will attempt to perform an uncrewed Lunar landing and ascent to validate the technologies needed for future Crewed Lunar landings.

title: Demo Flight
location: LC-16, Cape Canaveral SFS, Florida, USA

title: Astrobotic Lunar Mission 3
location: LC-39A, Kennedy Space Center, Florida, USA
mission_data.title: Astrobotic Lunar Mission 3
mission_data.description: Astrobotic Technology's third mission to the moon's surface. This mission lands at an area of intense interest for science instruments, technology demonstrators, rovers, power systems, and other infrastructure. Astrobotic plans to carry lunar surface payloads, as well as offer satellite deployments for those looking to deploy to other destinations in cislunar space.

title: Project Kuiper
location: ELA-4, Guiana Space Centre, French Guiana, France
mission_data.title: Project Kuiper
mission_data.description: Project Kuiper is a mega constellation of satellites in Low Earth Orbit that will offer broadband internet access, this constellation will be managed by Kuiper Systems LLC, a subsidiary of Amazon. This constellation is planned to be composed of 3,276 satellites. The satellites are projected to be placed in 98 orbital planes in three orbital layers, one at 590 km, 610 km, and 630 km altitude.

title: Roman Space Telescope
location: LC-39A, Kennedy Space Center, Florida, USA
mission_data.title: Nancy Grace Roman Space Telescope
mission_data.description: The Roman Space Telescope is a NASA observatory designed to settle essential questions in the areas of dark energy, exoplanets, and infrared astrophysics. The telescope has a primary mirror that is 2.4 meters in diameter (7.9 feet) and is the same size as the Hubble Space Telescope's primary mirror. The Roman Space Telescope will have two instruments, the Wide Field Instrument, and the Coronagraph Instrument.
